anti-law enforcement. Well, I'm
pro-police, I'm pro-law
enforcement, and I'm anti-police

12:30.750 --> 12:38.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
misconduct. I am anti-police
mistreatment. I am anti-police
discrimination.

12:38.024 --> 12:47.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When there is misconduct, that
officer needs to be, I will use
the word crucified, because

12:47.066 --> 12:54.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when one officer, whether it be
in a small town in New Jersey or
a major city on the

12:54.307 --> 13:00.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
West Coast or a mid-sized city
in Central United States,
anytime an officer commits

13:00.513 --> 13:07.020 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
misconduct, it reflects what I
have to deal with, what almost a
million other police officers

13:07.020 --> 13:09.122 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
have to deal with
around the country.

13:09.122 --> 13:14.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: When you see a
video or videos like the ones
that came out this week,

13:14.927 --> 13:18.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
as a member of the
African-American community, that
could have been a member of your
family,

13:18.531 --> 13:19.732 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
what goes through you?

13:19.732 --> 13:22.902 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
LT. THOMAS GLOVER: I'm
appalled that it happens.

13:22.902 --> 13:28.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I will be honest. I didn't cry,
the first one I saw that came
out of Baton Rouge. I

13:28.341 --> 13:34.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was very concerned. But the
second one that I saw in
Minnesota, I shed tears. I was
sitting

13:34.080 --> 13:38.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the sofa in my house, and I
began to cry and boo -- just
like I knew the person, because

13:38.985 --> 13:45.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I knew it was symbolic of a
major problem that we have in
this country.

13:45.124 --> 13:51.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As an African-American police
officer, every day that you
serve, it's almost like you're

13:51.197 --> 13:59.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
serving two masters. And I hate
to be so straightforward. Many
people expect us from the blue
side,

13:59.972 --> 14:07.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and I mean law enforcement, to
be quiet, to walk a tightrope,
and to just be indifferent.

14:07.213 --> 14:12.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On the other hand, in your
community, you are expected to
make a difference. I know

14:12.618 --> 14:17.390 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in all my years, I have heard
it, and now I have people
calling me saying, Glover, we

14:17.390 --> 14:22.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
told you so. You see it? A guy
got shot in the back running
away from a police officer,

14:22.829 --> 14:27.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and he never would have been in
trouble had not someone covertly
recorded it on a cell

14:27.066 --> 14:29.736 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
phone video.

14:29.736 --> 14:36.909 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And all I can do is say, yes,
you're right. We become adept at
doing both of them very

14:36.909 --> 14:43.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
well. We do the police job
extremely well, and we live in
our community extremely well,

14:43.349 --> 14:47.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but, sometimes, and oftentimes,
when you talk to
African-American police
officers, it's

14:47.820 --> 14:51.891 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one of the most grueling and
taxing things that you can do as
a human.

14:51.891 --> 14:59.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you saw it in a video that
went viral on Facebook this week
where the African-American

14:59.398 --> 15:05.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mother, who was a member of a
police department in Ohio
somewhere near Cleveland, a
seven-minute

15:05.004 --> 15:10.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
video of her screaming. And she
is vehemently and emphatically
denouncing the fact that

15:10.643 --> 15:17.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
she thinks very poorly -- and I
do, too -- of someone who
polices our community, whether

15:17.049 --> 15:23.790 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they be black, pink, purple or
green, and are so full of fear,
so full of fear, that

15:23.790 --> 15:26.159 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they mistreat people.

15:26.159 --> 15:28.161 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: When the
president comes, what do you
want to say to him? What do you

15:28.161 --> 15:30.663 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
want him to do?

15:30.663 --> 15:36.402 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LT. THOMAS GLOVER: Mr.
President, do the right thing.
I'm telling you, as a 35-year
African-American

15:36.402 --> 15:41.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
police officer, that there are
problems in the way we police in
the black community.

15:41.941 --> 15:46.078 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think you need to take
that charge, Mr. President, and
do whatever is necessary

15:46.078 --> 15:52.718 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to incite Congress to pass laws
that would allow us to rid the
law enforcement and the

15:52.718 --> 15:56.322 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
police profession of
these type of people.

15:56.322 --> 16:01.093 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now we get
several views about this moment,
some of the dividing lines and

16:01.093 --> 16:04.630 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
calls on all sides for change.

16:04.630 --> 16:08.701 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kasim Reed is the mayor of
Atlanta. He has been dealing
with protests throughout the

16:08.701 --> 16:13.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
weekend. The Reverend Jesse
Jackson, he's founder and
president of the Rainbow/PUSH

16:13.606 --> 16:19.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Coalition. He's one of the
country's most well-known civil
rights leaders. DeRay McKesson,

16:19.011 --> 16:24.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he's an activist co-founder of
Black Lives Matter. He was
arrested and released after

16:24.417 --> 16:29.689 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
protests in Baton Rouge this
weekend. And Julian Zelizer,
he's a professor of history

16:29.689 --> 16:34.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at Princeton University. He is
the author of "The Fierce
Urgency of Now," a book about

16:34.493 --> 16:37.663 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the battles over civil rights
and the Great Society.

16:37.663 --> 16:40.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And we welcome all of
you to the program.

16:40.366 --> 16:44.170 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Let me start with
you, DeRay McKesson.

16:44.170 --> 16:52.478 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Listening to Lieutenant -- we
just heard from Lieutenant Tom
Glover in Dallas. How divided

16:52.478 --> 16:57.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is this country, based on what
you have seen there in Louisiana
over the weekend? Where

16:57.884 --> 17:00.286 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
are we right now?

17:00.286 --> 17:03.055 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DERAY MCKESSON, Co-Founder,
Black Lives Matter: So, I don't
think that any of the division

17:03.055 --> 17:05.625 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or the tension is new.

17:05.625 --> 17:09.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What is new is that we're
finally having a public
conversation about this stuff.
So when

17:09.695 --> 17:13.332 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we think about the protests over
the last 22 months, they have
forced these issues of

17:13.332 --> 17:18.537 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
race, racism, criminal justice
to the forefront, specifically
focused on police violence.

17:18.537 --> 17:22.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm hopeful that more police
officers and more police chiefs
and police unions will

17:22.375 --> 17:26.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
come out acknowledging that the
culture of the police
departments are broken and that

17:26.379 --> 17:30.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there has to be change, that the
police don't get to operate
under a shadow justice system

17:30.616 --> 17:33.252 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and that we can live in a world
where the police don't kill
people.

17:33.252 --> 17:38.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Mayor Kasim
Reed, you were dealing with
protesters, as we said,

17:38.624 --> 17:44.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Atlanta over the weekend.
What did you see? And do you see
these conversations going

17:44.897 --> 17:48.401 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on across the country and in
your city making a difference
right now?

17:48.401 --> 17:52.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KASIM REED, Mayor of Atlanta,
Georgia: What I saw was an
expression of grief and pain

17:52.338 --> 17:57.910 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and frustration that
needed to be addressed.

17:57.910 --> 18:05.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I saw that people's First
Amendment rights needed to be
respected. We had 15,000
protesters

18:05.117 --> 18:11.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
since Thursday evening through
today. And I couldn't be prouder
of our law enforcement

18:11.791 --> 18:17.096 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
officials, the Atlanta Police
Department and the Georgia State
Patrol. We have had peaceful

18:17.096 --> 18:21.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
protests. We have had
minimal damage to property.

18:21.500 --> 18:27.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think that we have had
respect on both sides of the
conversation. And we have had

18:27.039 --> 18:33.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
less than 25 people arrested. We
take great pride in Atlanta in
being the home of Dr.

18:33.579 --> 18:38.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Martin Luther King and a number
of other civil rights leaders in
the United States, like

18:38.417 --> 18:42.688 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ambassador Andrew Young and
Congressman John Lewis. And
that's the way we approached the

18:42.688 --> 18:44.523 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
protests.

18:44.523 --> 18:48.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think that it made all of
the difference in how the
weekend turned out.

18:48.694 --> 18:53.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Reverend Jesse
Jackson, from the perspective
that you have from going back

18:53.666 --> 18:58.871 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the civil rights movement of
the 1960s, how do you look on
these protests of today

18:58.871 --> 19:03.476 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and how much progress do
you see having been made?

19:03.476 --> 19:05.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REV. JESSE JACKSON, FOUNDER,
Rainbow/PUSH Coalition: Well,
the protests are very
legitimate,

19:05.878 --> 19:10.783 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
because we're saying
that we matter.

19:10.783 --> 19:19.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When Trayvon Martin is killed
and the killer walks away, when
Rodney King is beaten and

19:19.325 --> 19:24.397 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is own camera and those who beat
him walk away, when Garner is
killed and they walk

19:24.397 --> 19:29.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
away, it's not just the act, but
the lack of consequences, when
violence occurs upon

19:29.568 --> 19:32.371 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
our people. And
that's a pattern.

19:32.371 --> 19:39.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a combination here, not
just police. Police --
federation are police who
control

19:39.145 --> 19:44.750 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the discipline, as well as
states' attorneys and judges,
and now prisons for profit. The

19:44.750 --> 19:49.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
whole judicial system has come
down on us and it's not right,
it's not fair. And the

19:49.321 --> 19:51.223 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
protests are legitimate.

19:51.223 --> 19:55.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I will only say that violence
takes away our moral authority.
We have the moral high road,

19:55.027 --> 19:58.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and keep that high road.

19:58.531 --> 20:01.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Julian Zelizer,
you are watching all this as
well. You have written about
this

20:01.367 --> 20:03.869 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a great deal.

20:03.869 --> 20:07.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you see the country coming
together in any regard at this
point? Or do we still have

20:07.940 --> 20:10.076 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
a long way to go
before that happens?

20:10.076 --> 20:12.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JULIAN ZELIZER, Princeton
University: We have a long way
to go.

20:12.778 --> 20:18.851 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're in a very divisive,
political moment right now, and
one of the possibilities is

20:18.851 --> 20:25.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the response to this is not
to find solutions to the
problems of policing that we
have seen,

20:25.224 --> 20:31.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but to move in a very different
direction. 1968, Richard Nixon
pushed the country toward

20:31.197 --> 20:35.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
law and order, rather than
reforming the criminal justice
system, and there is a
possibility

20:35.601 --> 20:38.437 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
we see the same
thing happen today.

20:38.437 --> 20:42.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I think the divisions are
real, they're deep, and I think
it's not unlike some of

20:42.241 --> 20:44.310 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what we saw in the late '60s.

20:44.310 --> 20:48.781 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: DeRay McKesson --
go ahead. Were you just
speaking?

20:48.781 --> 20:50.850 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REV. JESSE JACKSON: I was about
to make a point here that...

20:50.850 --> 20:52.118 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Reverend
Jackson, go ahead.

20:52.118 --> 20:54.787 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REV. JESSE JACKSON: ... it's
not just policing poverty.

20:54.787 --> 21:01.293 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We would ask for a White House
conference on policing, but also
on poverty, the racial

21:01.293 --> 21:05.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
disparity and the plan for
reconstruction. Changing -- if
you have a size 10 shoe in

21:05.865 --> 21:11.237 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a size 8 foot, it's not a
conversation. You need a shoe
that fits the foot.

21:11.237 --> 21:15.508 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Our poverty is twice the
national average, number one
infant mortality, number one in

21:15.508 --> 21:20.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
short life expectancy, lack of
access to capital and industry.
We have not recovered from the

21:20.412 --> 21:23.215 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
economic crisis yet. We
need reconstruction.

21:23.215 --> 21:28.487 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let me use
that as an opportunity to turn
back to DeRay McKesson

21:28.487 --> 21:33.859 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and ask you, what is it that the
Black Lives Matter movement, as
you see it, is looking

21:33.859 --> 21:35.761 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for?

21:35.761 --> 21:43.636 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Are you looking for --
specifically for police reform,
and where does it fit on the
spectrum

21:43.636 --> 21:48.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
between that and the much bigger
goals that Reverend Jackson is
talking about?

21:48.374 --> 21:52.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DERAY MCKESSON: So, Reverend
Jackson is right that there are
so many things that we need

21:52.578 --> 21:55.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to focus on. I think that what
is true is that what got people
on the streets in August

21:55.714 --> 21:59.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of 2014, when the movement was
born, was the death of Mike
Brown.

21:59.985 --> 22:03.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that -- there is something
visceral about the violence of
the police, that it continues

22:03.522 --> 22:06.825 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be something that people
organize around, and that is
central. That does not mean it's

22:06.825 --> 22:10.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the only thing that people focus
on. People are doing incredible
work around making sure

22:10.429 --> 22:14.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that we close the racial wealth
gap, on education, and that work
continues.

22:14.500 --> 22:18.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's the beauty of the
movement in a sense, is that it
wasn't -- there's no one,

22:18.370 --> 22:22.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
two, or three founders of the
movement. I'm certainly not a
founder of any space, but

22:22.308 --> 22:26.478 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I am one of many people doing
work in the space and we see so
many people right now

22:26.478 --> 22:31.584 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
finding their voice. We saw the
protesters in Atlanta
beautifully raising issues and

22:31.584 --> 22:35.588 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
being really clear about
solutions, and in Chicago, Baton
Rouge, and so many other places.

22:35.588 --> 22:39.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think it is rooted in the
violence of the police right
now, because the police kill

22:39.892 --> 22:43.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nearly three people -- have
killed nearly three people
already in 2016. But there are

22:43.896 --> 22:45.497 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people doing really good work
around the racial wealth gap and
education and so many other

22:45.497 --> 22:47.733 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
things.

22:47.733 --> 22:53.472 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mayor Reed, what
we're hearing there is that the
goals -- that there's a

22:53.472 --> 22:58.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
long list of goals of many
different kinds, and that -- I
think we're hearing about a

22:58.177 --> 23:01.413 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
movement that's more
decentralized than what we saw
during the civil rights
movements of

23:01.413 --> 23:02.915 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the '60s.

23:02.915 --> 23:07.886 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Does that mean it's more likely
to be successful or not?

23:07.886 --> 23:13.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KASIM REED: I think it's likely
to be successful because,
despite the fact that the
country

23:13.425 --> 23:18.230 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is in a tough time, we continue
to make forward movement.

23:18.230 --> 23:24.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, for example, in the city of
Atlanta, we have had our
officers have bias training.

23:24.603 --> 23:29.875 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So one of the issues that Black
Lives Matter's members and
others have raised is this bias

23:29.875 --> 23:35.914 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that many of us are
frequently unaware of.

23:35.914 --> 23:41.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The population of our police
department really mirrors our
city's population. That's
another

23:41.520 --> 23:48.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
issue that has been repeatedly
raised. Last year, in 1.6
million interactions with the

23:48.460 --> 23:54.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
public, our police officers
fired their weapons less than 10
times.

23:54.099 --> 23:59.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many of the changes and reforms
that we have experienced is
because we are actually
listening

23:59.605 --> 24:05.311 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the protesters and to others
and trying to respond. We have a
citizen review board

24:05.311 --> 24:11.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with subpoena power. So the
point I'm making is, is that it
is a very tough time, but
leaders

24:11.550 --> 24:17.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who are forward-thinking and
want America to be a better
version of itself are listening

24:17.356 --> 24:23.996 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very closely and trying to move
without having to respond to a
terrible tragedy.

24:23.996 --> 24:24.797 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

24:24.797 --> 24:26.999 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
REV. JESSE JACKSON: I'm
sorry. Forgive me.

24:26.999 --> 24:30.469 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Let me just --
just a second, Reverend Jackson.

24:30.469 --> 24:34.640 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I want to ask Julian Zelizer, is
there enough listening going on,
though? Because there's

24:34.640 --> 24:39.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
