last sitting Republican
presidents.

32:11.596 --> 32:14.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: The current
Republican governor.

32:14.166 --> 32:19.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMY WALTER: Or the current
Republican governor, or the 2012
nominee for the party.

32:19.905 --> 32:24.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I don't think that that's
the bigger problem for Donald
Trump. I think it is -- his
challenge

32:24.009 --> 32:29.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has long been he's done very
well in a primary that was very
narrow focused to a certain

32:29.147 --> 32:32.350 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
group of voters. He has yet to
make the case to a broader group
of voters. Can he do that

32:32.350 --> 32:35.420 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in this convention?

32:35.420 --> 32:40.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is his second chance that
he's getting, when people are
tuning in to see, has Donald

32:40.392 --> 32:44.696 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Trump turned the corner from
primary candidate to general
candidate?

32:44.696 --> 32:49.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Tomorrow in New
Hampshire on the Democratic
side, Bernie Sanders finally
shows

32:49.234 --> 32:54.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
